"(1) (i) The air inside the observation dome shimmered with a faint, electric undertone, as if the very glass was charged with the memory of a storm long past but not gone. Henry’s breath fogged the cold viewport, his gloved fingers tightening around the data tablet. Outside, the endless dunes of Mercury’s night side stretched like a silver river under the pale glare of distant orbital lights.\n(2) He could hear the low hum of life support systems, steady and reassuring—until it wasn’t. (ii) A flicker in the plasma display panel beside him caught his eye first—a tiny, almost imperceptible stutter in the containment field’s readouts. He frowned, tapping the screen with a stylus, rerunning the last few cycles.\n(3) The numbers should have been smooth as a falling star’s tail. Instead, there was a stutter, a stutter that grew, rippling through the grid like a shiver down a wire. (iii) Before Henry could react, the warning chime blared—a sound unlike any alarm he’d heard, oscillating between synthetic and something almost organic.\n(4) The magnetic containment field, designed to hold the superdense plasma core in place, began to falter. He watched, transfixed, as the shimmering barrier pulsed violently, then fractured with a sound like the splitting of thunder across steel. Mercury Twilight Observatory.\n(5) (iv) . That was the official designation etched in the metal frame above the entrance, its letters glowing faintly in the dim. May 28, 2225. Henry Reed. witnessed a magnetic confinement rupture.\n(6) Now, the structure trembled as the breach widened, a spiraling vortex of ionized gas and raw magnetic flux tearing through the chamber. The artificial gravity"